&#xa0;
defaultCabinet Officedefault – Written evidencedefault&#xa0;defaultDELEGATED POWERS AND REGULATORY REFORM COMMITTEEdefaultDRAFT DEREGULATION BILLdefault&#xa0;defaultIntroduction default&#xa0;default1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis Memorandum has been prepared for the Joint Committee which is scrutinising the Deregulation Bill in draft form (‘the Bill’) and for the consideration of the Delegated Powers and Regulatory Reform Committee. 
default2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe memorandum identifies the provisions of the Bill which confer powers to make delegated legislation. It explains in each case why the power has been taken and the nature of, and reason for, the procedure selected. 
default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSince the Bill deals with diverse subject areas, and covers changes from a number of departments, each measure is addressed individually. Most powers are specific to individual clauses but the Bill also includes some general powers. The material for the Memorandum was prepared by the relevant departments and drawn together by the Cabinet Office.
defaultBackground default&#xa0;default4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Deregulation Bill is a cross-Government Cabinet Office-led Bill. It forms part of the government’s commitment to reduce the overall burden of regulation and to cut ‘red tape’ during this Parliament. The implementation of that programme includes measures given effect by administrative changes and secondary legislation. The Bill is one of a number 
defaultof
default government bills that is taking forward reforms where their implementation requires primary legislation. Its purpose is to change various pieces of legislation in 
defaultorder
default to reduce or remove unnecessary legislative burdens on businesses, civil society, the taxpayer and individuals; and, additionally, to repeal some redundant legislation. 
default5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Bill includes measures relating to general and specific areas of business, companies and insolvency, the use of land, housing, transport, communications, the environment, education and training, entertainment, public authorities and the administration of justice. It also provides for a duty on those exercising specified regulatory functions to have regard to the desirability of promoting economic growth. It repeals some legislation that is no longer of any practical use, and provides ministers with a power to make similar repeals in the future via secondary legislation. 
defaultProvisionsdefault which confer defaultdelegated powersdefault default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultprovisions
default in the Bill which confer these powers are identified below. The purpose of the delegated powers taken, and an explanation as to why the matter is to be left to delegated legislation and why the relevant department has chosen a particular procedure, are then set out in relation to each relevant clause.  
default&#xa0;
defaultTerritorial coverage default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAny amendment of existing legislation has the same extent as the original legislation except where specified by clause 63(2) and (3). Clause 63(2) and (3) specify certain paragraphs in 
defaultSchedule 16, which repeal
default legislation which is no longer of practical use. 
default8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBy virtue of clause 63(5), the new powers granted to a Minister of the Crown by clauses 49 (power to amend legislation to describe actual commencement dates), 51
default-57
default (power to 
defaultdisapply
default legislation which is no longer of practical use) 
defaultand 58-61
default (provisions concerning the promotion of economic growth) form part of the law of England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. The provisions concerning consequential changes, commencement and short title set out in clauses 62, 64 and 65 also so apply, by virtue of the same clause. 
defaultDevolution
default9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExcept where the contrary is expressly stated, the powers conferred by the Bill are not exercisable in a devolved area. 
defaultClause 1: defaultHealth and safety at work: general duty of self-employed personsdefault&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultPower conferred on:
default              
default              
defaultThe Secretary of State 
default&#xa0;
defaultPower exercisable by:
default              
default              
defaultRegulations made by statutory i
defaultnstrument 
default&#xa0;
defaultParliamentary procedure:
default              
default Negative Resolution
default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default&#xa0;
default10.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis clause provides the Secretary of State with a new regulation-making power under the Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974
default.
default11.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSection 3(2) of the 1974 Act imposes a general duty on all self-employed persons to conduct their undertaking in such a way to ensure, so far as reasonably practicable, that they themselves and persons other than their employees who may be affected by it are not exposed to risks to their health and safety. 
default12.
default&#xa0; 
defaultClause 1 limits the scope of section 3(2) so that only those self-employed who conduct a “relevant undertaking” will continue to hold a duty under this provision.
default13.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis 
defaultnew regulation-making 
defaultpower is exercisable in relation to England and Wales and Scotland. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of the 
defaultprovision
default&#xa0;
default14.
default&#xa0; 
defaultClause 1(3) defines “relevant undertaking” as an undertaking of a prescribed description, or any other undertaking that could expose other persons to risks to their health and safety. 
default15.
default&#xa0; 
default“Prescribed” has a specific meaning within the 1974 Act, defined in section 53(1) as prescribed by regulations made by the Secretary of State. Clause 1(3) therefore enables the Secretary of State to make regulations for the purpose of bringing the
default self-employed within the scope of the section 3(2) duty. 
defaultUnless a relevant undertaking has been prescribed, a self-employed person will only owe a duty to themselves if their undertaking poses a risk of harm to others.
default16.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe regulation-making power in clause 1(3) affords the Secretary of State a degree of flexibility because a number of different 
defaultdescriptions  of
default an  undertaking could be given in the regulations. For example, a “prescribed description” could be by reference to the activities that the undertaking engages in (e.g. construction
default) ,
default the hazardous substances it uses, or a combination of these things. 
default17.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Secretary of State can exercise this power at his or her own discretion, or 
defaulton  a
default recommendation from the Health and Safety Executive who, by virtue of section 11(3) of the 1974 Act, may submit to the Secretary of State such proposals as it considers appropriate for the making of regulations. 
default18.
default&#xa0; 
defaultKey stakeholders will be consulted and their responses taken into account prior to a relevant undertaking being prescribed.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification 
defaultof 
default the
default delegation
default&#xa0;
default19.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe department considers it necessary for the Secretary of State to be given a separate regulation-making power to prescribe a relevant undertaking because 
defaultit  will
default give the assurance that those self-employed persons working in high hazard industries or engaging in  high hazard activities (who would be expected to pose the highest risks of harm to others, as well as themselves) will not be exempt from the general duty under section 3(2) of the 1974 Act. This approach will make it clear and unambiguous to those working in high risk industries that they will not be exempt from section 3(2), and that they will still have a duty to conduct their undertaking in such a way as to ensure that they and others are not exposed to risks to their health and safety. 
default&#xa0;
default20.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt is appropriate for relevant undertakings to be prescribed through secondary legislation because it is anticipated that the kind of undertaking that needs to be prescribed may be subject to change and require regular updating to reflect fluctuating or emerging risks associated with a variety of different workplace activities or sectors. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of Parliamentary scrutiny
default&#xa0;
default21.
default&#xa0; 
defaultRegulations made under the power conferred by clause 1(3) will be subject to the negative resolution procedure.  Section 82(3)
default of the 1974 Act 
defaultprovides that any power to make regulations conferred by Part 1 of the Act 
default( which
default includes section 3) shall be exercisable by statutory instrument and subject to annulment (subject to an exce
defaultption set out in section 82(4), 
defaultwhich is not relevant here). 
default&#xa0;
default22.
default&#xa0; 
defaultStatutory instruments made under this clause will not make amendments to primary legislation, therefore the additional procedural hurdles and increased occupation of Parliamentary time associated with the affirmative procedure is not considered appropriate. However
default,
default these regulations will effectively bring individuals within the scope of the primary legislation. Accordingly, the department considers the negative resolution procedure provides the appropriate level of scrutiny for detailed and technical provisions regarding health and safety at work.
default&#xa0;
defaultClause 3 and defaultScheduledefault 1: English apprenticeships: simplification – inserts defaultsectionsdefault default A1default to defaultA7 into the Apprenticeships, Skills, Children and Learning Act 2009default&#xa0;
defaultSection A1 (2) and A1 (4) and (5): Approved English apprenticeship
default&#xa0;
defaultPower conferred on:
default              
default              
defaultThe Secretary of State 
default&#xa0;
defaultPower exercisable by:
default              
default              
defaultRegulations made by statutory i
defaultnstrument 
default&#xa0;
defaultParliamentary procedure:
default              
default Negative Resolution
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default&#xa0;
default23.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSection 
defaultA1(
default2) sets out the meaning of an approved English apprenticeship for the purposes of the new Chapter A1 of the 
defaultApprenticeships, Skills, Children and Learning Act 2009 (“the 2009 Act”). 
defaultIt is an arrangement which either takes place under an approved English apprenticeship agreement or is an alternative English apprenticeship and, in either case, satisfies any conditions specified in regulations made by the Secretary of State.  Section 
defaultA1(
default4) confers a power on the Secretary of State to describe the kind of arrangements which are alternative English apprenticeships for the purposes of the new Chapter. 
default&#xa0;
default24.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe background is that Schedule
default 1 inserts a new Chapter A1 in Part 1 of 
defaultthe 2009 Act. 
defaultChapter 1 currently provides a regime for both English apprenticeships and Welsh apprenticeships. The new Chapter 
defaultA
default1 relates only to English apprenticeships. The existing Chapter 1 will continue to apply to Welsh apprenticeships.
default&#xa0;
default25.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe new provisions follow a review of apprenticeships by Doug Richard in 2012. He recommended that the government improve the quality of apprenticeships and introduce more employer focus. Chapter A1 simplifies the existing system. It introduces new concepts of approved English apprenticeships and approved apprenticeship standards.
default&#xa0;
default26.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Secretary of State has power to make regulations requiring the apprenticeship and the apprenticeship agreement to satisfy specified conditions. The Secretary of State also has the power to issue certificates to those who complete an approved English apprenticeship. The provisions as a whole reduce bureaucratic burdens, for example by abolishing apprenticeship frameworks and the issuing authorities who issue them.
default&#xa0;
default27.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThese 
defaultnew delegated 
defaultpowers are exercisable in
default relation to
default England only.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of new section 
defaultA1(
default2) 
default28.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSection A1(2) provides a power for the Secretary of State to specify conditions which must be satisfied in 
defaultorder
default for an arrangement to be an approved English apprenticeship for the purposes of the new Chapter A1. The Department envisages that this power will be used to specify common requirements that all apprenticeships must meet.  These common requirements may change from time to time and therefore it would be inappropriate to specify them in primary legislation.  For example, the Secretary of State may wish to specify a minimum duration to allow all apprentices sufficient time to practise and embed the skills they have learned. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of new section 
defaultA1(
default4) &amp; (5)
default29.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSection 
defaultA1(
default4) and (5) provide a power for the Secretary of State to describe the kinds of arrangements which constitute alternative
default English apprenticeships.  The d
defaultepartment envisages that the Secretary of State will use this power to describe arrangements which are suitable for apprenticeships, but where the arrangements cannot satisfy the employment requirements of an approved English apprenticeship agreement.  
defaultRegulations made under a similar existing power at section 1(5) of the 2009 Act exist for certain occupations where the apprentice is part of a crew or collective in the fishing, creative or performance industries. Regulations also exist for elite athletes undertaking the Sporting Excellence Apprenticeship with the hope of competing in 
defaultthe
default Commonwealth or Olympic Games.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation: new section 
defaultA1(
default2)
default30.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe main elements of approved English apprenticeships – apprenticeship agreements, approved apprenticeship standards, and certificates are set out in the new sections. Following consultation with employers and other stakeholders, it is very likely that further detailed conditions will be identified as being ones that all apprenticeships should meet
default,
default 
defaultf
defaultor example a minimum duration, a minimum amount of off-the-job learning, or minimum levels of English and maths 
defaultachievement t
defaulthat need to be acquired to complete an apprenticeship.  These requirements may change from time to time, for example in response to changes in policy priorities, or as new English and maths qualifications become available or their titles change.  As such it would be inappropriate to specify them i
defaultn primary legislation, and the d
defaultepartment considers that the use of delegated powers to specify conditions that must apply to an approved English apprenticeship is appropriate.  
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation: new section 
defaultA1(
default4) and (5)
default&#xa0;
default31.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe power to describe the kind of arrangements which constitute alternative English apprenticeships is similar to the power currently contained in section 1(5) of the 2009 Act to specify alternative English completion conditions. It is envisaged that
default the power will be used by the d
defaultepartment for the same purpose. 
defaultThe department
default is encouraging the use of more innovation within apprenticeships and a new apprenticeship standard can be developed at any time.  Delegation allows for the creation of an 
defaultapprenticeship  in
default exceptional circumstances, for example in certain circumstances where a person is self employed, or where a sector and individual could benefit from an approved apprenticeship.  Delegation will require detailed consideration of the merits of any application for an alternative English apprenticeship.  A
default 
defaultneed to use primary legislation would inevitably lead to delay and difficulty in keeping up with developments, and might constrain flexibility within the system.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of p
defaultarlia
defaultmentary s
defaultcrutiny
default32.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe department considers that the use of the negative procedure to specify conditions that must apply to an approved English 
defaulta
defaultpprenticeship is appropriate. Section 262(5) makes the current (and similar) regulation making power subject to the negative procedure.
default33.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe d
defaultepartment also considers the use of the negative procedure to describe the kinds of arrangements which constitute alternative English apprenticeships to be appropriate.  
default34.
default&#xa0; 
defaultRegulations on alternative apprenticeships under the current law first came into effect in 2012 and were amended in 2013 using the affirmative procedure.  On both occasions only cases of genuine merit were proposed and on both occasions the 
defaultR
defaultegulations were approved unanimously and without controversy.  In 2013 three formal requests for alternative English completion conditions were received.  Of those only one was recommended for inclusion in the regulations and even this one was subject to considerable challenge before it went forward.  The department believes it has proved effective at weeding out cases that are not appropriate for apprenticeships. The sifting of requests has become largely an administrative act, and has not proved to be controversial or of wide interest.
default35.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAs a result, the department does not consider that the additional cost, procedural hurdles and occupation of Parliamentary time associated with the affirmative procedure (which applies under the current law) are appropriat
defaulte to these powers; a change to 
defaultthe 
defaultnegative  procedure
default will enable the Secretary of State to act more swiftly where necessary to encourage innovation within apprenticeships and to respond to the nation’s needs at lower overall cost to the public purse. 
default&#xa0;
