default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default46.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis section provides the Secretary of State with the power to make provision about applications for apprenticeship certificates, the supply of copies of apprenticeship certificates and the charging of fees for the issue of a certificate or supply of a copy.
default47.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis power is exercisable in relation to England only. 
defaultThe effect of the section
default48.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe d
defaultepartment envisages that the Secretary of State will use these powers to replace certificates (for example if these have been lost by the individual), or 
defaultto charge a fee for issuing and - or 
default- 
default replacing
default certificates.  This will be beneficial to the individual as it will give them evidence of their apprenticeship and the achievement of their apprenticeship, which they will find helpful when, for example, seeking a new job.  
defaultJustification of the Delegation
default              
default49.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThese powers replace the powers in sections 3 and 4 of the 2009 Act (so far as relating to English apprenticeships). The new sections as a whole will simplify the current system by removing the role of English certifying authorities. In future there may be situations where an apprenticeship certificate may not be required to be issued, for example where a trade specific certificate is the main recognisable standard for a particular occupation.  The use of the delegated power will regulate the supply of certificates and enable the Secretary of State to charge a fee for issuing or supplying a certificate.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of parliamentary s
defaultcrutiny
default50.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe supply of copy certificates and the charging of fees for this or for the issue of an apprenticeship certificate is largely an administrative task and the department considers that the use of the negative procedure is appropriate.  
default&#xa0;
defaultClause 4 and defaultScheduledefault 2: Driving Instructors default&#xa0;
defaultPower conferred on:
default              
defaultThe
default 
defaultSecretary of State
defaultPower exercised by:
default              
defaultRegulations made by statutory instrument
defaultParliamentary procedure:
default 
default              
defaultNegative resolution
default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default51.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe amendments made by 
defaultSchedule
default 2 provide for a single system of registration for driving instructors which applies to both instructors who are disabled and those who are not. 
default&#xa0;
default52.
default&#xa0; 
defaultUnder the new system the Registrar of Approved Driving Instructors will have power to require a person, whether disabled or not, to undergo an assessment as to their ability to control a  vehicle in an emergency (“an emergency control assessment”) and to issue a certificate where satisfied of the person’s ability to do so (“an emergency control certificate”).
default&#xa0;
default53.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe new system requires changes to the regulation-making powers in Part 5 of the Road Traffic Act 1988. 
default&#xa0;
default54.
default&#xa0; 
defaultPart 1 of 
defaultSchedule
default 2 amends Part 5 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 in the form it will be in once the amendments made to it by the Road Safety Act 2006 come into force.  Part 2 of 
defaultSchedule
default 2 amends Part 5 as it has effect before those amendments come into force.  
default55.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThese powers are exercisable in 
defaultrelation to 
defaultEngland and Wales and Scotland
default.
defaultThe effect of Part 1 of 
defaultSchedule
default 2
defaultParagraph 2(a) – amending section 124(3)
default&#xa0;
default56.
default&#xa0; 
defaultUnder section 123 a person is prohibited from giving paid driving instruction of any prescribed
default description unless registered in respect of that description. Regulations under section 124 may prescribe circumstances in which the section 123 prohibition does not apply. In particular, regulations may be made so that in prescribed 
defaultcircumstances persons who are training to be driving instructors are not required to be registered. Section 124(3) sets out particular circumstances which may be so prescribed. Paragraph 2(a) of 
defaultSchedule
default 2 amends section 124 so as to make it clear that those circumstances could include the circumstance that a person holds a current emergency control certificate. This would allow regulations to be made to exempt trainee driving instructors from the requirement to register in circumstances where the trainee holds an emergency control certificate.
defaultParagraph 3(3) – amending section 125
default57.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSection 125A of the 1988 Act is repealed by paragraph 5 of 
defaultSchedule
default 2. However, the definitions of “disability” and “relevant disability” given by section 
default125A(
default8) are still required for the purposes of Part 5 of the 1988 Act, as amended. Accordingly, paragraph 3(3) amends section 125 to reproduce the definitions. This has the effect of preserving the current power to prescribe by regulations a disability which is to be treated as a relevant disability for the purposes of the Part.   
defaultParagraph 4(2
default)(
defaultb) – amending section 125ZA(2)
default58.
default&#xa0; 
defaultUnder section 125ZA(1) the Registrar must register a person in respect of a description of driving instruction if the person makes an application for registration and the Registrar is satisfied that the prescribed conditions are met. Section 125ZA
default 
default(2) sets out what conditions may, in particular, be prescribed. Paragraph 4(2) amends section 125ZA so as to add conditions requiring a person who has been required to submit to an emergency control assessment to hold a current emergency control certificate. 
defaultParagraph 4(3
default)(
defaulta) and (d) – amending section 125ZA(4)
default59.
default&#xa0; 
defaultUnder section 125ZA(3) a person may be registered in respect of a description of driving instruction subject to fulfilling prescribed conditions so long as the person continues to be registered. Section 
default125ZA(
default4) sets out what conditions may, in particular, be prescribed. Paragraph 4(3)(a) amends section 125ZA so as to add-
default&#xad;
default(a) 
defaultconditions
default requiring a person to submit to an emergency control assessment (if required to do so by the Registrar in the circumstances mentioned in section 125(3D));
default(b) 
defaultconditions
default requiring a person to hold an emergency control certificate following such an assessment;
default(c), conditions requiring that, if instruction is to be given in circumstances where there is a reasonable expectation of an emergency arising which necessitates the instructor taking control of the vehicle, a person will only give such instruction if they would be able to take control of the vehicle if such an emergency arose.  
defaultParagraph 11(4) and (5) – amending section 
default133A(
default2) and (6) 
default60.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSection 133A
default 
default(2) sets out in full the meaning of “emergency control assessment”. It refers to an assessment of a person’s ability to take control of a vehicle of a class 
defaultcovered by the disabled person’s limited driving licence. This is no longer appropriate as, under the new system, people who are not disabled may also be required to undertake emergency control assessments. Paragraph 11(4) therefore amends section 
default133A(
default2) to refer instead to an assessment of a person’s ability to take control of a motor vehicle of a prescribed class. Paragraph 11(5) makes a consequential amendment to section 
default133A(
default6) which deal with the issue of emergency control certificates.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of Part 2 of 
defaultSchedule
default 2
defaultParagraph 17(2)
default&#xa0;
default61.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis paragraph inserts a new section 125(2C) and (2D) which sets out the circumstances in which the Registrar may require an applicant for registration to submit to an emergency control assessment. The circumstances are that the Registrar has reasonable grounds for believing that the applicant would be unable to take control of a motor car of a prescribed class if an emergency arose while he was giving driving instruction. 
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultParagraph 17(4) – amending section 125(5)
default62.
default&#xa0; 
defaultUnder section 125(5) continued 
defaultregistration
default as an approved driving instructor is subject to the condition that the instructor will, upon request by the Registrar, submit to a test of continued ability and fitness to instruct. Paragraph 17(4) amends section 125(5) to add a further condition that the person will, if required to do so by the Registrar, submit to an emergency control assessment on a day within such period as may be prescribed.  
default&#xa0;
defaultPar
defaulta
defaultgraph 17(7) – amending section 125
default63.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis paragraph inserts section 125(8A) and (8B) which prevent a person making  a further application for registration if the person  has undergone an emergency control assessment, been refused an emergency control certificate and, in consequence,  either not been registered or had their name removed from the register. The person is  prevented from making a further application before the end of the period of 6 months , beginning with the date of the assessment, or before the end of such other period as may be prescribed, unless the Registrar is satisfied that there is good reason for allowing an earlier application.  
default&#xa0;
defaultParagraph 17(9) – amending section 125(10)
default64.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSection 125A of the 1988 Act is repealed by paragraph 18 of 
defaultSchedule
default 2. However, the definitions of “disability” and “relevant disability” given by section 
default125A(
default8) are still 
defaultrequired for the purposes of Part 5 of the 1988 Act, as amended. Accordingly, paragraph 17(9) amends section 125 to reproduce the definitions. This has the effect of preserving the current power to prescribe by regulations a disability which is to be treated as a relevant disability for the purposes of the Part.
default&#xa0;
defaultParagraph 23(3) – amending section 129
default65.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis paragraph inserts a new section 129(1B) and (1C) which set out the circumstances in which the Registrar may require a person who applies for a licence for the purpose of gaining experience in giving driving instruction to submit to an emergency control assessment. The circumstances are that the Registrar has reasonable grounds for believing that the applicant would be unable to take control of a motor car of a prescribed class if an emergency arose while he was giving driving instruction.
default   
defaultParagraph 23(4) – amending section 129(2)
default66.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn consequence of the new system, paragraph 23(4) substitutes a new section 129(2) to set out the circumstances in which the Registrar must grant a licence to persons seeking to gain experience in giving driving instruction. The amendment preserves the existing power to prescribe a fee for the granting of such a licence. 
default&#xa0;
defaultParagraph 23(6) – amending section 129
default67.
default&#xa0; 
defaultUnder section 129(5) a licence granted for the purpose of enabling a person to gain experience in giving driving instruction may be granted subject to prescribed conditions. Paragraph 23(6) amends section 129 to provide that those conditions may include-
default(a) 
defaulta
default condition requiring the person granted the licence, if required to do so by the Registrar at a time when the circumstances in section 129(1C) apply, to submit to an emergency control assessment within a prescribed period;  
default(b) 
defaulta
default condition requiring that, if driving instruction is to be given in circumstances where there is a reasonable expectation of an emergency arising which necessitates the instructor taking control of the car, a person will only give such instruction if they  would be able to take control of the car if such an emergency arose. 
default&#xa0;
defaultParagraph 25(4) 
defaultand (5) – amending section 
default133A
default(
default2) and (6)
default68.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSection 
default133A(
default2) sets out in full the meaning of “emergency control assessment”. It refers to an assessment of a person’s ability to take control of a motor car of a class covered by the disabled person’s limited driving licence. This is no longer appropriate as, under the new system, people who are not disabled may also be required to undertake emergency control assessments. Paragraph 25(4) therefore amends section 
default133A(
default2) to refer instead 
defaultto an assessment of a person’s ability to take control of a motor car of a prescribed class. Paragraph 25(5) makes a consequential amendment to section 
default133A(
default6) which deals with the issue of emergency control certificates
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation
default69.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe amendments to Part 5 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 set out above expand the existing powers to make regulations in relation to driving instruction under that Part. The department continues to consider that the power to make such provision should be delegated to the Secretary of State as a regulation-making power. The detail of such provisions is more appropriate to secondary legislation. There is also likely to be a need to amend such provisions and make further provision from time to time which would be less conveniently achieved if contained in primary legislation.  
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of p
defaultarliamentary scrutiny
default70.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe negative resolution procedure applies, by virtue of section 195(3) of the Road Traffic Act 1988, to the existing powers to make regulations under Part 5 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 and the department continues to believe that this is appropriate. There should be Parliamentary scrutiny as the new powers extend to matters which are important to becoming and remaining a driving instructor but these are not so significant as to merit the affirmative procedure. 
