default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default71.
default&#xa0; 
defaultClause
default 7 provides for the amendment of
default Part 3, sections 20 and 21, of the Clean Air Act 1993 
defaultwhich deals with 
defaultSmoke Control Areas
default.
default 
defaultUnder Part 3, it is an offence to emit smoke from the chimney of any building, or to emit smoke from a chimney (not being a chimney of a building) which serves the furnace of any fixed boiler or industrial plant, within a smoke control area unless using an authorised fuel or exempted appliance.  It is also an offence under section 23 to acquire or sell an unauthorised fuel within a smoke control area unless it is to be used under the specified requirements of an exempted appliance.
default&#xa0;
default72.
default&#xa0; 
defaultCurrently the Secretary of State has the power under sections 20 and 21 of the Clean Air Act 1993 to authorise fuels by regulations and to exempt 
defaultclasses of fireplaces by 
defaultorder
default.  The regulations and 
defaultorder
default are made by statutory instrument. They are made every six months (April and September) in England to coincide with the common commencement dates.  
default&#xa0;
default73.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAuthorised fuels and exempted fireplaces are not identified individually within the Clean Air Act 1993 but have been the subject of the power of delegated legislation as this allows new fuels and fireplaces to be authorised and exempted as they are developed. This Bill includes a modification to the
default 
defaultprocedure by which thi
defaults delegated power is exercised.
default74.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis change to the procedure applies in relation to
default England only.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the change in delegation
default75.
default&#xa0; 
defaultManufacturers submit their products for testing to determine whether they are capable of being used without producing any smoke or a substantial quantity of smoke. The results are then checked by authorised contractors who subsequently make recommendations to the Secretary of State for inclusion in the six monthly 
defaultSIs
default.
default 
default76.
default&#xa0; 
defaultUnder the Red Tape Challenge
default,
default 
defaultthe 
defaultGovernment made a commitment to simplify the process of exemption and authorisation, with a view to reducing burdens and improving efficiency.  Interested parties advised that the main burden associated with the current process was the delay between receiving a recommendation from authorised contractors and subsequent inclusion in the SIs.
default&#xa0;
default77.
default&#xa0; 
defaultTo reduce the burden associated with the delay the Bill will amend sections 20 and 21 of the Clean Air Act to provide the Secretary of State with powers to authorise fuels and exempt appliances administratively by the publication of lists
default, thus avoiding 
defaultthe need for the production of the six monthly 
defaultSIs
default.  The government intends that this power would be exercised by publishing lists on the gov.uk website. Initial lists of authorised fuels and exempt appliances would be published upon the commencement of this provision; these lists would include the products approved under the existing SIs to ensure that these do not lose their approved status. Thereafter updated versions of the lists would be published on a monthly basis as new products are approved.  This will allow manufacturers to bring their products to market more rapidly and allow consumers access to latest 
defaultthe 
defaulttechnology.  The new procedure would enable lists to be updated and published as deemed necessary and if changes are required these will be made on a specific date each month.  The published lists will include details of the product type, conditions of use and date of grant, withdrawal
default or variation of any approval.
default Consumers without internet facilities may obtain access to the information via the 
defaultDefra
default Helpline
default or by writing to or emailing the d
defaultepartment direct.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification 
defaultof the level of parliamentary s
defaultcrutiny
default78.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn 
defaultorder to qualify for
default inclusion in the published lists, products must continue to meet the current requirements to demonstrate they are capable of being used without producing any smoke or a substantial quantity of smoke, therefore the safety and eligibility of these products for use in smoke control areas will remain unchanged. List publication and amendment will be subject to a robust system of quality controls and approval by senior staff.  The dates that products are added to the lists will be specified as will the dates of 
defaultany  variations
default or withdrawals of approvals. This will ensure that there is legal certainty with respect to which products may or may not be used, or, in the case of fuels, sold and acquired for use in a smoke control area at any given point in time.  
default&#xa0;
default79.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe offences under sections 20 and 23 regarding the emission of smoke and the sale and acquisition of fuels for use within a smoke control area are not changed by the 
defaultB
defaultill.  
default&#xa0;
default80.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe authorisation or exemption of a product would only be withdrawn if evidence which demonstrates that the product does not meet the eligibility criteria for use in a smoke control area came to light. 
defaultThe department
default is not aware of any appliance exemption being withdrawn to date.  Some authorised fuels have been removed in the past as manufacture had ceased and the fuel had not been available for many years.  Variations of authorisations and exemptions have previously consisted of changes to brand name or manufacturer’s name and the SIs have indicated any previously known names for clarity.  It is not intended to change this process.
default&#xa0;
default81.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn the event of evidence indicating that a product authorisation should be withdrawn 
defaultthe department
default would liaise with interested parties first to investigate the validity of the evidence and then to ensure the withdrawal is publicised appropriately and where possible consumers are notified of the withdrawal.  The new centralised lists will highlight the date at which any withdrawals or amendments were made which is an improvement on the current system where it would be necessary to compare lengthy product lists in the SIs in 
defaultorder
default for consumers and 
defaultlocal authorities 
defaultto identify any changes in the status of a product.  Finally there are some inherent additional legal safeguards to protect consumers and manufacturers.  The first of these is the requirement in the Clean Air Act 1993 to publish the lists.  The other is that a decision to withdraw an authorisation/exemption would be subject to judicial review if it is not taken correctly.  
