default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default92.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis clause inserts new section 519A into the Companies Act 2006 (“the Act”). Subsection (1) defines 
defaultlisted
default company and, also, non-
defaultlisted
default company, for the purposes of Part 16 (removal, resignation, etc of auditors). 
default&#xa0;
default93.
default&#xa0; 
defaultA 
defaultlisted
default company is defined as a company whose “transferable securities” (these include shares and bonds) are included in the “official list” – in other words they have a main (London Stock Exchange) market listing – or whose shares are listed on a comparable market elsewhere in the EEA. A non-
defaultlisted
default company is defined as a company that is not a 
defaultlisted
default company.
default&#xa0;
default94.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn the context of auditors ceasing to hold office and the amendments to the Act being made by clause 10, there is a distinction between a 
defaultlisted
default company and a non-
defaultlisted 
defaultcompany and an enhanced framework of regulatory requirements applies in the case of the former. For instance, if an auditor of a 
defaultlisted
default company is ceasing to hold office that auditor must in all cases send the company a statement of reasons as to why he or she is stepping down. If an auditor of a non-
defaultlisted
default company is ceasing to hold office, however, that requirement does not apply in all cases – it applies where an auditor leaves before the end of his or her term and either one or more of the auditor’s reasons for leaving is of regulatory interest or there are matters which the auditor thinks the company’s shareholders or creditors should know about.  
default&#xa0;
default95.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe sending of such a statement leads in turn to other obligations on the part of the auditor or the recipient – for instance, the company must (generally speaking) send a copy of such to a statement to its shareholders and creditors and to the Registrar of Companies.
default&#xa0;
defaultDevolution
default96.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe new order-making
default power
default conferred by the 
defaultclause 
default is
default exer
defaultcisable in relation to 
defaultEngland and Wales, 
defaultScotland and Northern Ireland
default. In relation to 
defaultNorthern 
defaultIreland, this i
defaults a transferred area. Discussions with the devolved administration about seeking a legislative consent motion. 
defaultThe effect of the 
defaultprovision
default97.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSubsection (5) of new section 519A provides that the Secretary of State may by 
defaultorder
default amend the definition of 
defaultlisted
default company. Since a non-
defaultlisted
default company is simply defined as a company that is not a 
defaultlisted
default company, amending the definition of 
defaultlisted
default 
defaultcompany
default 
default will
default simultaneously have the effect of altering what is a non-
defaultlisted
default company. 
default&#xa0;
default98.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAmending the definition of 
defaultlisted
default company may be a relatively trivial matter – markets may change over time and the power could, for instance, be used to update terms and references used in the then current definitions (the power may already have been used of course) that have become obsolete. The power could, however, be used to provide that certain types of company, in respect of which the enhanced framework does not apply, will thereupon be subject to that framework. An example would be amending the definition to include companies that are listed on secondary markets or which are currently unlisted but, because of their size or the sector in which they operate, are of 
defaultconsiderable economic or public importance.  Conversely, the power could be used to amend the definition to exclude a type of company from the list of 
defaultcompanies  in
default respect of which the enhanced framework applies.   
default&#xa0;
default99.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSubsection (6) of new section 519A provides that an 
defaultorder
default pursuant to new subsection (5) is subject to the negative resolution procedure.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation
default100.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAmending the definition of 
defaultlisted
default compa
defaultny is justified because of the department
default’s wish for flexibility as regards keeping the current (and any future) definitions up-to-date and as regards determining precisely what type of company will or will not be covered by the enhanced framework of auditor leaving statement requirements.     
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of parliamentary s
defaultcrutiny
default101.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOn balance, and notwithstanding that this is a Henry VIII power, the department considers that the negative resolution procedure is appropriate. This is because, and as explained above, such a power might only be used in a very minor way – bringing references and terms used in the then current definitions up-to-date. Even if the power is used in a more material way, there will be cases in which there are no practical consequences. For instance, where the power is used to add new types of company (and thereby apply the enhanced framework to the same), the auditor of such a company may be sending the company a leaving statement in a case in which, prior to the exercise of the power, he would also have had to have sent such a statement – i.e. because he or she was leaving prior to the end of his or her term and, for example, there were matters which he or she thought the company’s shareholders needed to know about.  Moreover, these are technical, regulatory matters such that in any event the use of the power is not expected to attract widespread interest or be controversial. In th
defaulte circumstances, the d
defaultepartment does not consider that the a
defaultdditional procedures and p
defaultarliamentary engagement associated with an affirmative resolution procedure statutory instrument can be justified. 
default&#xa0;
default102.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are a number of existing Henry VIII powers on the face of the Act in respect of which the negative resolution procedure applies and which might therefore be considered a precedent. Section 857(1) is a power to make regulations further providing for the contents of a company’s annual return and subsection (2) provides that these regulations may amend the existing provisions at sections 855 and 856. Section 1099(4) relates to the Registrar of Companies obligations to keep an index of the names of companies and other bodies and allows the Secretary of State by 
defaultorder
default to amend the list of other bodies at section 1099(3). Section 1160(1) is a power to make regulations amending the definitions of “subsidiary”, “holding company” or “wholly-owned subsidiary” – see section 1159 of and 
defaultSchedule
default 6 to the Act. Note that, like the proposed power to amend the definition of “public interest 
defaultcompany
default”, each of these powers may be used in material way - making bodies or other persons subject to new obligations or, conversely, 
defaultremoving obligations to which bodies or other persons are subject.  
default&#xa0;
default103.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPlease note that the department
default is considering whether it would be preferable to replace the terms ‘listed company’ and ‘non-listed company’
default with alternative labels before the Bill is introduced in Parliament. 
default  
default&#xa0;
defaultClauses 13 – 17; and clause 18, which introduces defaultScheduledefault 6 default&#xa0;
defaultGeneral introduction to the ‘rights of way’
default provisions
default104.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBy way of general background to these measures, Part 3 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (“the 1981 Act”) requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area. The local authorities concerned are referred to in that Act as “surveying authorities” and the maps and statements are referred to as “definitive maps and statements”. Part 3 also sets out the procedures which apply where an authority wishes to make a change to the definitive map and statement for its area or where someone applies for such a change to be made.
default&#xa0;
default105.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA definitive map and statement is conclusive evidence of certain matters. For example, if a map shows a footpath, this is generally conclusive evidence that the public had a right of way on foot over the land on a particular date.
default&#xa0;
default106.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome rights of way are not recorded on a definitive map and statement. Section 53 of the Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 (“the 2000 Act”). 
defaultprovides
default for unrecorded rights of way created before 1949 to be extinguished immediately after 1 January 2026 (known as the “cut-off date”), subject to certain exceptions. 
default&#xa0;
default107.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 2000 Act also confers power on the Secretary of State to, by regulations, make transitional provisions and savings, in particular for cases where (a) orders modifying definitive maps and statements have been made but not confirmed before the cut-off date; (b) applications for definitive map orders have been submitted before the cut-off date; or (c) orders have been quashed because of a legal error (section 56(2
default)(
defaultb)).
default&#xa0;
default108.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Highways Act 1980 (“the 1980 Act”) also deals with public rights of way. For example, it allows applications to be made, in certain circumstances, to extinguish or divert a public right of way.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default109.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe new delegated powers conferred by the rights of way provisions in the Bill 
defaultare  exercisable
default in relation to England only. 
default&#xa0;
defaultClause 13: Unrecorded rights of way: protection from extinguishmentdefault&#xa0;
defaultPower conferred on
default: 
default              
defaultThe
default Secretary of State
defaultPower exercised by:
default              
defaultRegulations made by statutory instrument. 
default(Extension of existing regulation making power.)
defaultParl
defaultiamentary procedure: 
default              
defaultNegative R
defaultesolution
default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default110.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis clause provides the Secretary of State with a method to protect certain public rights of way from extinguishment in 2026. 
default&#xa0;
default111.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe general background to this, as explained in the general introduction to 
defaultthe rights of way provisions
default, is that Part 3 of the 1981 Act requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area. 
default&#xa0;
default112.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome rights of way are not recorded on a definitive map and statement. Section 53 of the 2000 Act provides for the extinguishment, immediately after cut-off date, of unrecorded rights of way created before 1949, subject to certain limited exceptions. 
default&#xa0;
default113.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThat Act also confers power on the Secretary of State to, by regulations, make transitional provisions and savings (see the general introduction to 
defaultthe rights of way provisions for further details of this.) 
default&#xa0;
default114.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is thought that, in the period immediately before the cut-off date, there will be a large volume of applications to surveying authorities for modifications to be made to the definitive map and statement to show rights of way that are currently unrecorded. This is because individuals and groups in the voluntary sector are likely to carry out research so that they can make applications to have unrecorded rights of way shown on a definitive map and statement (with the result that they will not be automatically extinguished after that date). There is concern that surveying authorities will also carry out research into unrecorded rights of way during this period in order to comply with the requirement that they keep under review definitive maps and statements. This could lead to surveying authorities unnecessarily duplicating the work of individuals and the voluntary sector.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of the 
defaultprovision
default115.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe clause therefore inserts a new section 56A in the 2000 Act. This extends the regulation-making power in section 56(2) of that 
defaultAct  to
default enable the Secretary of State to make regulations enabling a surveying authority to designate, during a period of one year after the cut-off date, public rights of way extinguished immediately after that date under section 53 of that Act. The exercise of the power is subject to the negative resolution procedure (see section 56(6) of that Act).  The new section 56A also sets out what else may be included in the regulations. It is envisaged that the power to make regulations will be used to provide for designated rights to cease to be regarded as extinguished as from the time of designation. Where a right is designated, surveying authorities will be required to decide whether to modify the definitive map and statement to show the right of way. If a right of way is then sho
defaultwn on the map, it will remain non-
defaultextinguished. If the authority decides not to show the right of way, it will normally be extinguished again. 
default&#xa0;
default116.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultProvision may also be made as to the procedure applicable in relation to such a determination. The provision that may be made by virtue of subsection (1
default)(
defaultd) includes provision applying 
defaultSchedule
default 15 to the 1981 Act, subject to such modifications as may be specified in the regulations.
default&#xa0;
default117.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultClause 13 is in the nature of a transitional or savings provisi
defaulton. It is about 
defaultthe  transition
default 
defaultto a position where certain unrecorded public rights of way will no longer be able to be added to definitive maps and statements. It also provides a method to save unrecorded rights that would otherwise be extinguished on the cut-off date. It enables surveying authorities to wait until after the cut-off date to assess what research has been carried out by individuals and voluntary organisations. There will be a one-year period after that date within which they can act under the regulations to prevent rights of way being permanently extinguished. They will therefore be able to avoid duplicating any work done by individuals and voluntary organisations and focus, during the one-year period following the cut-off date, on areas where research has not been carried out by individuals and voluntary organisations.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation
default118.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs explained above in the description of the effect of clause 13, the clause is in the nature of a transitional or savings provision. As explained in the general introduction to 
defaultthe rights of way provisions
default, the 2000 Act already confers power on the Secretary of State to, by 
defaultregulations,
default make transitional provisions and savings in relation to the cut-off date. 
defaultThe department
default therefore considers it appropriate that further provision for 
defaulttransition and savings is also 
defaultdealt with by delegated legislation. 
default&#xa0;
default119.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe department
default also considers it appropriate that the procedure for the determination in relation to a designated public right of way be dealt with by delegated legislation. Clause 13 provides that the provision that may be made by virtue of subsection (1
default)(
defaultd) includes provision applying 
defaultSchedule
default 15 to the 1981 Act, subject to such modifications as may be specified in the regulations. 
defaultThe department’s
default intention is to introduce a procedure that closely follows the procedure set out in 
defaultSchedule
default 15. However, due to the 
defaultfact that the procedure will apply for only a transitory period, and deal with designated public rights of way (and not rights of way generally), it is anticipated that various modifications of 
defaultSchedule
default 15 will be required. 
defaultThe department
default has not finalised the details of the modified procedure, and needs the flexibility afforded by the regulation-making power.
