default&#xa0;defaultIntroduction
default138.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis provision provides the Secretary of State with power to introduce a modified procedure for the correction of administrative errors in maps and statements of public rights of way.
default&#xa0;
default139.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe background to this, as explained in the general introduction to 
defaultthe rights of way provisions
default, is that Part 3 of the 1981 Act requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area.
default&#xa0;
default140.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSchedule
defaults 14 and 15 to the1981 Act set out the procedure which applies where an authority wishes to make a change to the definitive map and statement for its area or where someone applies for such a change to be made. There is provision for such things as the making of applications, the making of orders, notification, publicity, consultation, referral (of opposed orders), determination, and finally, confirmation. 
default&#xa0;
default141.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAdministrative errors, such as a reference accompanying a path on a map to “FP23” when the path is in fact “FP33”, are often found in definitive maps and statements. There is currently not any separate procedure to deal with such cases. Surveying authorities are expected to follow the procedure in 
defaultSchedule
defaults 14 and 15 to the 1981 Act. This is unnecessarily burdensome in cases where errors are obvious and very unlikely to be contentious. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe e
defaultffect of the
default provision
default142.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe provision therefore inserts a new section 53ZA in the 1981 Act. Under this provision the Secretary of State may introduce a modified procedure for the correction of administrative errors. The procedure must follow the existing procedure in 
defaultSchedule
defaults 14 and 15 with such modifications as are prescribed in regulations. Subsection (3) provides that the exercise of this power is subject to negative resolution procedure.
default&#xa0;
default143.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSubsection (1
default)(
defaulta) to (c) specifies the circumstances where surveying authorities may use the new procedure. Firstly, authorities must be satisfied that an event of the kind specified in section 53(3
default)(
defaultc) of the 1981 Act must have occurred (these are known as “evidentiary events”). An evidentiary event includes such things as the discovery by an authority that a public right of way shown on the definitive map of a particular description ought to be shown as a way of a different description.  Secondly, they must be satisfied that the need for the modification has arisen because of an administrative error. Thirdly, they must be satisfied that both the error and the modification needed to correct it are obvious. Surveying authorities must have regard to any guidance given by the Secretary of State in judging whether subsection (1
default)(
defaulta) to (c) has been met.
default&#xa0;
default144.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe purpose of the provision is to provide a method to introduce a shorter procedure for correcting administrative errors in definitive maps and statements.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation
default145.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe department
default envisages that the modified procedure will generally be same as the procedure in 
defaultSchedule
defaults 14 and 15 to the 1981 Act, with modifications to make it shorter and more appropriate given the subject matter of administrative errors. The existing procedure relating to changes to definitive maps and statements is prescribed in primary legislation. 
defaultThe department
default considers that the correction of administrative errors is important, but not so important as to require that the procedure for correcting administrative erro
defaultrs be subject to the degree of p
defaultarliamentary scrutiny associated with primary legislation. As explained above in the description of the effect of the provision, the clause sets out in detail the circumstances in which surveying authorities may use the modified procedure.
default&#xa0;
default146.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe department
default needs the flexibility afforded by a delegated legislative power. This will enable 
defaultthe department 
defaultto change procedure relatively quickly, in view of practical experience and changes in case law.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of parliamentary s
defaultcrutiny
default147.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs explained above in the description of the effect of the clause, the exercise of the power is subject to negative resolution procedure. As explained above the power to introduce a modified procedure is limited to relatively minor issues (administrative errors). 
defaultThe department 
defaultconsiders therefore that the negative resolution procedure is appropriate and proportionate.
