default148.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis provision provides the Secretary of State with a method to specify that the duty to keep a register of applications under Part 3 of the 1981 Act does not apply to certain applications.
default&#xa0;
default149.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs described above in the general introduction, Part 3 of that Act requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review definitive maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area. Part 3 also sets out the procedures which apply where someone applies to a surveying authority for a change to be made to a definitive map and statement. 
default&#xa0;
default150.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSection 
default53B(
default1) of that Act requires surveying authorities to keep a register of applications. Section 53B(6) provides that where section 53B mentions “prescribed” this means prescribed by the Secretary of State by regulations subject to the negative resolution procedure.
default&#xa0;
default151.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultParagraph 6(4) inserts a new subsection (4A) into section 53B of the 1981 Act. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of the provision
default&#xa0;
default152.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe new provision states that regulations may provide that section 53B(1) does not apply with respect to applications made in England, or to any prescribed description of such applications, unless the authority serve notice under paragraph 1A(4)(b) of 
defaultSchedule
default 14 in relation to such an application. The effect of this is to confer a new delegated legislative power on the Secretary of State.
default&#xa0;
default153.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultParagraph 1A(4)(b) refers to notice being given of an authority’s decision to determine an application having concluded under paragraph 1A that there is a reasonable basis for the applicant’s belief that the definitive map and statement should be changed.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the d
defaultelegation
default154.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe department’s
default policy is that the duty to register applications generally should not apply with respect to applications made in England, unless the authority has served notice as described above. However, 
defaultthe department
default is still considering whether it might wish to make exceptions to this general policy in respect of certain categories of application. 
defaultThe department
default therefore needs the flexibility afforded by the delegation of legislative power. Section 53B(1) and (6) also provides a precedent for conferring delegated power on the Secretary of State to prescribe the information that might be contained in the register in regulations. 
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of parliamentary scrutiny
default155.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSection 
default53B(
default6) provides a precedent for regulations subject to the negative resolution procedure for prescribing the information that must be kept in the register. Whilst the exclusion of information from the register of all applications for changes to definitive maps and statements is an important matter, 
defaultthe department 
defaultdoes not consider it so important that the affirmative resolution procedure ought to apply. There is very little public interest in applications for changes to definitive maps and statements where there is no reasonable basis for such changes to be made. However, the private landowner over whose land the alleged right subsists, may have some, albeit mild interest in an application notwithstanding that there is no reasonable basis for it. 
defaultThe department
default therefor
defaulte considers that some level of p
defaultarliamentary scrutiny is merited and that the negative resolution procedure is appropriate and proportionate. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultClause 18 and defaultScheduledefault 6 paragraph 5: Modifications of definitive map by consent: Englanddefault&#xa0;
defaultPower conferred on: 
default              
defaultSurveying authorities
defaultPower exercised by:
default              
defaultOrder
default 
defaultParliamentary procedure: 
default              
