default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default189.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPermit schemes are designed to control the carrying out of specified works in the area covered by the scheme. Permit schemes cover both street works and works carried out by the local highway authority. A permit must be sought from the relevant local authority for works which are to be carried out in a street covered by a permit scheme. Currently, permit schemes prepared by local highway authorities in England must, before they are implemented, be submitted to the Secretary of State for approval and given effect to by an 
defaultorder
default made by the Secretary of State. This clause removes the requirement that the Secretary of State must approve and give effect to a permit scheme by 
defaultorder
default.
default&#xa0;
default190.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPart 3 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 provides for permit schemes. Section 34 concerns the implementation of local highway authority permit schemes. Section 34(2) provides 
default(in relation to England) 
defaultthat a permit scheme, previously submitted to the Secretary of State for approval, may be approved with or without modifications. Section 34(4) provides that a permit scheme shall not have effect unless the 
defaultSecretary of State
default gives effect to it by 
defaultorder
default.  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default191.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe changes made by the Bill provide local highway authorities with a new power to give effect to permit schemes by order. The new power is exercisable in relation to 
defaultEngland only.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of the 
defaultprovision
default192.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis clause, by the insertion of Part 1 of 
defaultSchedule
default 8 to the Bill makes certain amendments to Part 3 of the Traffic Management Act 2004. A new section 33A (Implementation of local highway authority permit schemes: England) is inserted into Part 3 and replaces the requirement for the Secretary of State to give effect to a local highway authority permit scheme, by requiring that the local highway authority give effect by 
defaultorder
default to a permit scheme in its area. 
defaultThe authority can also vary or revoke a permit scheme by order. 
defaultSuch an 
defaultorder
default will be a local council 
defaultorder
default, which will not be a statutory instrument.  Accordingly, local highway authorities will be able to prepare and give effect to their own permit schemes.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation
default193.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe requirement for the Secretary of State to approve permit schemes is no longer required, given the generally high quality and consistency of such schemes. Providing local highway authorities with the ability to prepare and approve their own schemes is consistent with the principles of localism and removes an additional and unnecessary administrative layer which has resource considerations for the Secretary of State and local highway authorities. As local highway authorities will, in accordance with the 
defaultclause, prepare their own permit schemes it is entirely logical that they give effect to such schemes, as the Secretary of State will no longer have an approval role. 
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of parliamentary s
defaultcrutiny
default194.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSection 39(2) of the Traffic Management Act provides for the Secretary of State’s current power to make an 
defaultorder
default giving effect to a permit 
defaultscheme  to
default be exercisable by statutory instrument. No parliamentary process is prescribed for such 
defaultorder
defaults and accordingly they are not laid before Parliament. Accordingly, although permit schemes will no longer be brought into effect by statutory instr
defaultument as there is currently no p
defaultarliamentary scrutiny of 
defaultorder
defaults made by the Secretary of State, the proposed ch
defaultange will not reduce or weaken p
defaultarliamentary scrutiny. Permit schemes will still be evidenced by a formal a
defaultdministrative decision but the d
defaultepartment considers that process should be placed in the hands of the authority that prepares and is to operate a permit scheme.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultClause 23(b) and defaultScheduledefault 8, Part 2 – road humpsdefault&#xa0;defaultPower conferred on: 
