defaultIntroduction
default215.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPart 6 does not introduce a new delegated power, but amends the procedure that applies to an existing exemption 
defaultorder
default making power. 
default&#xa0;
default216.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSection 183(1) of the Equality Act 2010 enables the Secretary of State by 
defaultorder
default to grant exemptions from rail vehicle accessibility regulations (RVAR). 
defaultCurrently the scrutiny procedure for an exemption 
defaultorder
default is either the affirmative or negative procedure. The Secretary of State decides, on the basis set out in the Rail Vehicle Accessibility Exemption 
defaultOrder
defaults (Parliamentary Procedures) Regulations 2008, which procedure will apply. 
default217.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThese powers are exercisable in relation to England and Wales and Scotland
default.
defaultThe effect of the 
defaultprovision
default218.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPart 6 will amend the 2010
default Act so that exemption 
defaultorder
defaults no longer need to be made by statutory instrument but can instead be made and amended by administrative 
defaultorder
defaults issued by the Secretary of State.  Consequently the parliamentary scrutiny procedures that currently apply to exemption 
defaultorder
defaults will no longer apply. 
default219.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe principal benefit of Part 6 will be to reduce the resources required by 
defaultthe department 
defaultin processing exemption applications to their conclusions.  This is because the resources needed to produce an administrative 
defaultorder
default will be less than those required for preparing a statutory instrument and taking it through the parliamentary scrutiny process. The change will also save parliamentary time. In addition the 
defaultdepartment 
defaultexpects there to be a small benefit to applicants from the change by speeding up the process, so giving a decision sooner.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the use of administrative 
defaultorder and the level of p
defaultarlia
defaultmentary s
defaultcrutiny
default220.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe scope of RVAR has been reduced since a similar proposal was made in the past (see below), such that they no longer apply to rail vehicles that are subject instead to EU accessibility rules. These rules require new, upgraded or renewed vehicles to comply with the technical specifications for interoperability for persons with reduced mobility (PRM TSI). The EU accessibility regime applies to mainline services, i.e. the majority of train services. RVAR now applies only to a minority (approximately one quarter) of rail vehicles – mostly light rail such as tramways, metros and underground. The two regulatory regimes have similar technical requirements.
default221.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe EU accessibility regime is implemented in the UK by the Railways (Interoperability) Regulations 2011. One difference between the two regimes is that exemptions from RVAR are made by statutory instrument, while exemptions from the PRM TSI can 
defaultby
default made in Great Britain by the Secretary of State making an administrative determination, subject in some cases to the approval of the European Commission – see regulation 14 of the 2011 Regulations. Removing the requirement for RVAR exemption 
defaultorder
defaults to be made by statutory instrument will therefore bring the light rail regime more in line with the EU regime, which we believe is more proportionate, particularly given that other safeguards will remain.
default222.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe requirement in the Equality Act 2010 for the Secretary of State to consult the Disabled Persons Transport Advisory Committee (DPTAC
default) before granting an exemption is unchanged, as is the requirement for him to make an Annual Report to Parliament on the use of the exemption powers.  
defaultThe department
default believe
defaults
default that DPTAC’s continued involvement in considering the merits of each application will ensure that the needs of disabled people are given appropriate weight, while the Annual Report will allow Parliament to consider whether the powers had been used excessively in the past year and call Ministers to account if it so wished.
default&#xa0;
default223.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultdepartment
default made clear during consultation that there would be no reduction in the strength of argument required before an exemption was granted.  More background information about the proposal is set out in the 
defaultdepartment
default’s March 2013 consultation, which can be found with a summary of the consultation responses at:
defaulthttps://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/proposed-changes-to-exemptions-from-rail-vehicle-accessibility-requirements
default 
default&#xa0;
default224.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA large majority of those who responded to the consultation supported the proposal, including DPTAC.
default&#xa0;
default225.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA similar proposal was made when the Disability Discrimination Bill was considered by Parliament before it became the Disability Discrimination Act 2005. That similar proposal was considered by the Delegated Powers and Regulatory Reform Committee and the Committee recommended that the proposal was not enacted - see paragraph 9 of the Committee’s Fourth Report for the Session 2004-5. In the end the Disability Discrimination Act 2005 amended the Disability Discrimination Act 1995 maintaining the requirement for parliamentary scrutiny in all circumstances, with the procedure being either the negative or affirmative procedure. The rail vehicle accessibility provisions of Disability Discrimination Acts, without significant further change, were re-enacted in the Equality Act 2010.
default&#xa0;
default226.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn its Fourth Report for the Session 2004-5 the Committee was concerned about the lack of evidence to support the proposal – see paragraph 7. The 
defaultdepartment 
defaultnow considers that it does have sufficient evidence and in particular points to the improved efficiency in public administration and the predominately supportive responses to the proposal following the recent consultation. An impact assessment for this measure will be available before introduction of the Bill to Parliament.  The 
defaultdepartment 
defaultalso believes that the large reduction in the scope of RVAR that has taken place since th
defaulte proposal was first considered
default justifies looking at this issue again. 
