default&#xa0;
defaultClause 48: defaultAmbulatory references to international shipping instrumentsdefaultPower conferred on: 
default              
default              
defaultHer Majesty in Council and/or Secretary of State
defaultPower exercised by: 
default              
default              
defaultRegulations made by s
defaulttatutory instrument/Direction 
defaultParliamentary procedure: 
default              
defaultVaries (as explained further below)
defaultIntroduction
default&#xa0;
default303.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis clause amends the Merchant Shipping Act 1995 so that the powers to make secondary legislation wherever they appear in that Act can be exercised so as to provide for a reference in the legislation to an international agreement to be interpreted as a 
defaultreference to the agreement as modified from time to time. 
default&#xa0;
default304.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe current practice of implementing international maritime 
defaultconventions,
default and regular changes to them, by means of a mixture of primary legislation and secondary legislation has resulted in a complex regulatory structure that is confusing to industry and the regulator alike. It is also time consuming and resource intensive, leading to delays in implementation – which in turn can result in ships being challenged during inspections in foreign ports leading to delays and inconvenience to UK ships.
default&#xa0;
default305.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe clause has been designed to address these issues by making it possible to streamline the incorporation of the provisions of international maritime conventions so that, where it is considered appropriate to do so, the government would not need to make further secondary legislation or publish any other regulatory document in 
defaultorder
default to give effect to changes to international obligations and standards; changes to the text of an international agreement would be automatically incorporated into UK law in the circumstances specified in the secondary legislation.
default306.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis power 
defaultis exercisable in relation to England and 
defaultWales, Scotland and Northern Ireland
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of the 
defaultprovision
default307.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe clause provides that the existing powers to make secondary legislation contained in the Merchant Shipping Act may be exercised so as to make ambulatory provision.  It also provides that the operation of the ambulatory reference may be 
defaultdis
default-applied or delayed.  It is not proposed to consider each of the individual powers to make subordinate legislation affected, which are subject to different parliamentary procedures; some of which already allow what are in effect ambulatory references to be made in certain circumstances.  This memorandum will consider two issues.  The first being the principle of allowing ambulatory references in secondary legislation, the second being the power of direction provided for in subsection (5) which would have the effect of limiting the operation of the ambulatory reference.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation
default308.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe principle of allowing ambulatory references in legislation is now well established most notably in paragraph 1A(1) which was added to 
defaultSchedule
default 2 of the European Communities Act 1972 by section 28 of the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006.
default&#xa0;
default309.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultInternational instruments in the marine sector such as SOLAS (the International Convention for the Safety of Life at Sea) and MARPOL (the International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution from Ships) are often of a highly technical nature specifying standards of construction, equipment and procedures that must be complied with.  
defaultBecause of the international nature of shipping operations once the provision come into force they must be complied with by the UK shipping industry where it operates in the territorial waters of a signatory country, irrespective of whether the UK has incorporated the relevant requirements into its domestic law.  In addition once the UK has become a party to an international instrument which has come into force it is under an obligation to apply the terms of that instrument both to its own ships and, usually, to ships of other nations operating within its jurisdiction.  
default&#xa0;
default310.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn some cases therefore allowing a change to an international instrument to take effect through the operation of an ambulatory reference in the manner proposed in this clause represents the most timely and cost effective method of providing certainty to the industry and allowing the UK to comply with its international obligations.
default&#xa0;
default311.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Subsection (5) provides that secondary legislation may authorise the Secretary of State to give a direction wh
defaultich will have the effect of 
defaultdis
defaultapplying
default or delaying the operation of the ambulatory provision.  
defaultSubsection (6) extends this power of direction to include 
defaultdisapplying
default any provision of subordinate legislation to which the ambulatory provision relates and making alternative provis
defaulti
defaulton.
default 
defaultThe reason that the
defaultse
default power
defaults are
default being sought is that there may be occasions when it is necessary to delay or prevent an obligation which arises as a result of an ambulatory change from having effect 
defaultand in
default 
defaultsome cases make alternative provision
default.  Such instances are expected to be rare; an example might be where the new provision would be inconsistent with an existing EU law obligation which is likely to be the case where the EU adopts higher standards than are required by the international agreement.  
defaultIn such cases it would be important that the existing secondary legislation did not remain in force
default. 
defaultIt would of course be possible to achieve the same result by amending the secondary legislation which gives effect to the ambulatory provision.  However, this is likely to be difficult to achieve in the required timescale particularly where the instrument requires the affirmative process and 
defaultwould be inconsistent with the g
defaultovernment’s policy of reducing the number of statutory instruments required to implement the international obligations.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of parliamentary s
defaultcrutiny
default312.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs far as the exercise of delegation conferred by the making of the ambulatory reference itself is concerned this will only be possible where there is an existing power to make secondary legislation.  The level of scrutiny appropriate to the subject matter of such legislation will have already been co
defaultnsidered by Parliament and the d
defaultepartment sees no reason why, if an ambulatory reference is to be included in such legislation
default,
default that there should be any change to the level of scrutiny.  In a number of cases, particularly where the purpose of the legislation is to incorporate changes to the text of an international instrument, the secondary legislation is subject to the affirmative procedure.  Parliament will, in almost all such most cases, have the ability to consider the instrument containing the ambulatory reference under either the negative or affirmative procedure.
default&#xa0;
default313.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a further consideration which is that in most circumstances a change to UK law taking effect as a result of the operation of the ambulatory reference will only take effect following a change to an international agreement which will have been agreed to by the UK government and which will already been notified to Parliament. The only instances where this will not be are 
defaultcases  where
default the international instrument contains a process whereby supplemental provision can be made through the issue of a code or a standard or changes can be made to the terms of the instrument through the so called tacit agreement procedure whereby a change becomes effective and binds all the signatories of the agreement once a certain number of signatories have agreed.  However, in both cases the possibility of such changes being made without the further need for the explicit approval of the UK government was already present when the decision was made to accede to the agreement so this should not of itself demand additional scrutiny.   
default&#xa0;
default314.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs already noted to the extent that the power of the Secretary of State to issue directions 
defaultunder  subsection
default (5) is novel this should not necessarily mean that any additional scrutiny is needed.  Firstly, the inclusion of the power in secondary legislation will of it
defaultself be subject to the level of p
defaultarliamentary scrutiny that has already been considered appropriate for the relevant secondary legislation.  Secondly, the effect of the exercise of the power will 
defaultnormally 
defaultbe to preserve the existing le
defaultgal position. As a result, the d
defaultepartment does not consider the power should be subject to any additional procedure and that the additional cost, proced
defaultural hurdles and occupation of p
defaultarliamentary time associated with the making of a statutory instruments would not be appropriate in this case; the power will enable the Secretary of State to act more swiftly where necessary, and at lower overall cost to the public purse.
default&#xa0;
defaultClause 49 – power to spell out dates described in legislationdefault&#xa0;
defaultPower conferred on: 
default              
default              
defaultA Minister of the Crown
defaultPower exercised by: 
default              
default              
defaultOrder
default  made
default by statutory instrument
defaultParliamentary Procedure: 
default              
defaultN
defaultone
default&#xa0;
defaultIntroduction
default315.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultClause 49 confers a power on Ministers to amend legislation – primary and secondary - by statutory instrument in 
defaultorder
default to spell out dates described in it. So, for example, if a section of an Act refers to “the day on which this section comes into force”, the power would allow the actual date to be substituted, when it becomes known. The amendments to be made by secondary legislation are therefore editorial rather than substantive.
default&#xa0;
default316.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe purpose of the power is to improve the accessibility of legislation, so that those reading legislation will be able to see on the face of the legislation what the relevant dates are without having to look them up, for example by searching through commencement 
defaultorder
defaults. The power can be used on an ongoing basis, in relation to legislation passed or made after the enactment of the Bill, to replace references to commencement dates with actual dates as and when they become known, but it will also be possible to use it to amend references to commencement dates in existing legislation. 
default&#xa0;
defaultDevolution
default317.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis 
defaultpower
default  is
default exercisable in relation to England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. The power could therefore be used to change references to commencement in legislation which deals with a matter devolved to Scotland, Northern Ireland or Wales. In the light of this, discussions are taking place with the devolved administrations to ascertain whether it would be appropriate for legislative consent motions to be sought in respect of clause 49. 
default&#xa0;
defaultEffect of the 
defaultprovision
default318.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe effect of this clause is to provide a flexible mechanism through which legislation can 
defaultbe  edited
default to enable those reading it to readily understand when it came into force. 
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the delegation
default319.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is appropriate for the relevant amendments to be made by 
defaultorder
default made by statutory instrument so that they are accessible and published in the statutory instrument series.
default&#xa0;
defaultJustification of the level of parliamentary s
defaultcrutiny
default320.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposed new power is not subject to any form of parliamentary procedure. This is because the amendments made using the power will not involve any substantive policy decisions but will reflect decisions made previously. Similar powers have been included in previous legislation – for example, clause 7(2) of the Offender Rehabilitation Bill introduced in the House of Lords on 9 May. This power was not subject to any form of parliamentary procedure.  The Delegated Powers and Regulatory Reform Committee in their Report on that Bill said “we welcome the facility introduced by clause 7(2
default)(
defaulta), as we can see some real advantages for users of legislation in the replacement of references to commencement dates” (First Report of 2013/14; HL Paper 12). Clause 22(3) of the draft Pensions Bill, published on 2 January 2013, also included a similar power, although this was ultimately dropped as it became unnecessary.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
